      <div class="faq-item" data-category="basics">
        <div class="faq-question">
          <h3>What is the difference between Western and Vedic numerology?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle"><i class="fas fa-plus"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Western numerology (Pythagorean system) assigns numbers 1-9 to letters in a specific pattern (A=1, B=2, etc.) and focuses on birth date and name analysis. Vedic numerology (Chaldean system), commonly practiced in India, assigns numbers based on sound vibrations, uses 1-8 (with 9 considered divine), and incorporates more spiritual elements. Vedic numerology also places greater emphasis on name correction and remedial measures to enhance positive energies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="faq-item" data-category="calculations">
        <div class="faq-question">
          <h3>How do I calculate my Name Number in Vedic numerology?</h3>
          <span class="faq-toggle"><i class="fas fa-plus"></i></span>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>In Vedic (Chaldean) numerology, letters are assigned values: 1 (A, I, J, Q, Y), 2 (B, K, R), 3 (C, G, L, S), 4 (D, M, T), 5 (E, H, N, X), 6 (U, V, W), 7 (O, Z), and 8 (F, P). Add the values of all letters in your name and reduce to a single digit unless it's 11, 22, or 33. For example, "AMIT" would be 1+4+1+4=10, which reduces to 1. This system is widely used in traditional Indian numerology.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
